ng Championships|ECC]], [[Curling at the 2018 Winter Olympics|OG]], [[2018 World Men's Curling Championship|WCC]]\n|-\n| 2018\u201319 || '''Niklas Edin''' || Oskar Eriksson || [[Rasmus Wran\u00e5]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] || [[Daniel Magnusson (curler)|Daniel Magnusson]] || [[2018 European Curling Championships|ECC]], [[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|WCC]]\n|-\n| 2019\u201320 || '''Niklas Edin''' || Oskar Eriksson || [[Rasmus Wran\u00e5]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] || [[Daniel Magnusson (curler)|Daniel Magnusson]] || [[2019 European Curling Championships|ECC]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{worldcurling}}\n*{{worldcurlingtour}}\n*[http://litcurling.wordpress.com/ Lit CC Homepage]\n\n{{Footer World Mixed Doubles Curling Champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eriksson, Oskar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish male curlers]]\n[[Category:Curlers at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Curlers at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Curlers at the 2018 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Sweden]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Sweden]]\n[[Category:Olympic curlers of Sweden]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:World curling champions]]\n[[Category:European curling champions]]\n[[Category:Swedish curling champions]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2018 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in curling]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Karlstad]]\n[[Category:Continental Cup of Curling participants]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in curling]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for Sweden]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2013 Winter Universiade]]\n[[Category:Swedish Curling Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish curler from Karlstad|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox curler\n| name = Oskar Eriksson\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1991|5|29}}\n| birth_place =[[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]|\n| Curling club = [[Karlstads Curlingklubb|Karlstads CK]], <br> [[Karlstad|Karlstad, SWE]]\n| Skip = [[Niklas Edin]]\n| Third = '''Oskar Eriksson'''\n| Second = [[Rasmus Wran\u00e5]]\n| Lead = [[Christoffer Sundgren]]\n| Alternate = [[Daniel Magnusson (curler)|Daniel Magnusson]]\n| Mixed doubles partner = [[Anna Hasselborg]]\n| World Championship appearances = 9 (2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019)\n| World Mixed Doubles Championship appearances = 1 (2019)\n| European Championship appearances = 11 (2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019)\n| Olympic appearances = 3 (2010, 2014, 2018)\n| Grand Slam victories = 3 ([[The Masters Grand Slam of Curling|Masters]]: [[2016 WFG Masters|2016]]; [[GSOC Tour Challenge|Tour Challenge]]: [[2016 GSOC Tour Challenge|2016]]; [[Players' Championship]]: [[2017 Players' Championship|2017]])\n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[curling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{SWE}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 Winter Olympics|2018 Pyeongchang]]|[[Curling at the 2018 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Sochi]]|[[Curling at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Curling Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2013 Victoria]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2015 Halifax]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 World Men's Curling Championship|2018 Las Vegas]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|2019 Lethbridge]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 World Men's Curling Championship|2014 Beijing]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2017 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2017 Edmonton]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2011 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2011 Regina]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2012 World Men's Curling Championship|2012 Basel]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Mixed Doubles Curling Championships|World Mixed Doubles Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship|2019 Stavanger]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Curling Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 European Curling Championships|2009 Aberdeen]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 European Curling Championships|2012 Karlstad]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 European Curling Championships|2014 Champ\u00e9ry]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 European Curling Championships|2015 Esbjerg]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 European Curling Championships|2016 Renfrewshire]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 European Curling Championships|2017 St Gallen]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 European Curling Championships|2019 Helsingborg]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 European Curling Championships|2011 Moscow]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 European Curling Championships|2018 Tallinn]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Junior Curling Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 World Junior Curling Championships|2011 Perth]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2008 World Junior Curling Championships|2008 \u00d6stersund]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Winter Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 Winter Universiade|2013 Trentino]]|}}\n}}\n'''Oskar Eriksson''' (born 29 May 1991) is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Curling|curler]] from [[Karlstad]].<ref>2020 Continental Cup Media Guide: Team Edin</ref> He currently plays third for the [[Niklas Edin]] rink. He is a four-time World Curling Champion, seven-time European Curling Champion, and the first curler in history to win gold medals in three major curling championships in a single calendar year \u2013 the World Men's Curling Championship, the European Curling Championship, and the World Mixed Doubles Championship. He is the only member of Team Sweden to have competed in all of the World Men's Curling Championships from 2011 to 2019. He won medals in all but one of these championships, as well as playing in multiple positions \u2013 as skip (silver, [[2014 World Men's Curling Championship|2014]]), third (gold, [[2015 World Men's Curling Championship|2015]], [[2018 World Men's Curling Championship|2018]], [[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|2019]] and silver, [[2017 World Men's Curling Championship|2017]]) second (bronze, [[2012 World Men's Curling Championship|2012]]), and as an alternate (gold, [[2013 World Men's Curling Championship|2013]] and bronze, [[2011 World Men's Curling Championship|2011]]). As a member of Team Niklas Edin, he has also won three Grand Slam Curling Events, as well as the Pinty's Cup, being part of the first non-Canadian men's team to do so.\n\n==Career==\n===Career Beginnings===\nEriksson began curling before he was six years old. He followed his older brothers [[Anders Eriksson (Karlstad curler)|Anders Eriksson]] and [[Markus_Eriksson_(curler)|Marcus Eriksson]] into the sport, but his skill level advanced more rapidly.<ref name=Erikssonhistoria>{{cite web|url=https://www.vf.se/2019/12/24/plats-1-oskar-eriksson-skrev-historia-under-guldkantat-2019/|title=Plats 1: Oskar Eriksson skrev historia under guldkantat 2019|publisher=V\u00e4rmlands Folkblad |date= 24 December 2019|accessdate=2019-12-24}}</ref> He was part of a curling team at age seven,<ref name=Erikssonhistoria /> debuting in Sweden's Elite Series at the age of thirteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2009/12/30/framtiden-osaker-for-lag-eriksson/|title=Framtiden os\u00e4ker f\u00f6r Lag Eriksson|publisher=Nya Wermlands Tidningen|date= 30 December 2009|accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref> He won his first Swedish Men's Curling Championship title in his junior career and has gone on to win six more championship titles since then.<ref>[[Swedish Men%27s Curling Championship]]</ref>. As a junior, Eriksson also competed at three World Junior Curling Championships, winning both a gold medal and a silver medal. At those three World Junior Championships, Eriksson skipped two different Swedish teams, winning a total of 24 games and losing only 9.\n\nEriksson made his first run for a junior world championship title when he was sixteen at the [[2008 World Junior Curling Championships]], skipping his first team, consisting of Henric Jonsson, Markus Franz\u00e9n, and Nils Karlsson, to a silver medal, losing in the final to the US team skipped by [[Chris Plys]]. In 2008, Eriksson moved to H\u00e4rnosand to join other promising curlers at H\u00e4rnosands gymnasium.<ref name=Eriksson2008>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2009/01/06/oskar-kom-hem-och-vann/|title=Oskar kom hem \u2013 och vann|publisher=Nya Wermalands Tidningen|date= 6 January 2009|accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> He also joined Team Lits CC/Lindstr\u00f6m, formed by brothers [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] and [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] along with [[Christoffer Sundgren]] and [[Henrik Leek]]. The team had immediate success on the junior tour and also scored wins in the senior division.<ref name=Eriksson2008 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ltz.se/artikel/lag-lindstrom-bast-i-norska-elitserien |title=Lag Lindstr\u00f6m b\u00e4st i Norden|publisher=L\u00e4nstidningen \u00d6stersund|date= 12 October 2008|accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> With this team, Eriksson made his second run for the gold medal at the [[2009 World Junior Curling Championships]], but reached only a fourth-place finish, losing in the bronze-medal game to the US team that was again skipped by Plys. Though the team did not qualify to compete at the championships in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cuponline.se/teamView.aspx?cupid=318&id=4343|title=Junior SM 2010: Lits CC/Lindstr\u00f6m|publisher=CupOnline|date= 6 January 2010|accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> Eriksson and his teammates finally won a gold medal at the [[2011 World Junior Curling Championships]], defeating Team Switzerland, skipped by [[Peter de Cruz]], by a score of 6\u20135 in the final. In 2012, his teammates were no longer eligible for junior competition, so Eriksson skipped Team CK Granit-G\u00e4vle, consisting of Ludwig Grann, Erik \u00d6lund and Magnus Rudstr\u00f6m, at the 2012 Swedish Junior Curling Championships with the aim of qualifying for the World Junior Curling Championship. Erikssons team was undefeated until the finals, but there they came in second place to the team from Sundyberg skipped by his future teammate [[Rasmus Wran\u00e5]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cuponline.se/teamView.aspx?cupid=1570&id=17105/|title=Junior SM 2012: Granit-G\u00e4vle|publisher=CupOnline|date= 7 January 2012|accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Seniors I (2009-2014): Team Lindstr\u00f6m/Eriksson and Team Edin ===\n\nShortly after joining Team Lit in 2008, Eriksson played simultaneously with two teams. His official team during this period was Team Lit, alternatively known as Team Lindstr\u00f6m and eventually Team Eriksson. Eriksson skipped the team for most of this period through 2014.<ref>https://litcurling.wordpress.com/</ref><ref name=Erikssoncareer>{{cite web|url=https://worldcurl.com/player.php?playerid=14370&view=Teams |title=Oskar Eriksson, Career Results|publisher=WorldCurl.com |date= 5 April 2020|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> From 2009 through February 2014, he also effectively became the presumptive alternate for Team [[Niklas Edin]] with [[Niklas Edin]], [[Sebastian Kraupp]], [[Fredrik Lindberg]], and [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]], playing at the World Curling Championships, European Curling Championships, and 2010 and 2014 Olympic Games. During this period, however, Team Lit became more competitive with Team Edin and was well recognized as one of the top two men's curling teams in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2012/10/04/topplag-i-samma-bo |title=Topplag i samma bo|publisher=Nya Wermlands Tidningen |date= 4 October 2012|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAs an alternate for Team Edin during this period, Eriksson received numerous medals, including two gold medals at the European Curling Championships (2009 and 2012) and three World Curling Championship medals, including his first World Championship gold medal (2013) and two bronze medals (2011 and 2012). At the [[2012 World Men's Curling Championship]], however, he notably played in the second position for all games except three because Niklas Edin, the permanent skip, was suffering from a herniated disc in his back. Eriksson also played this position in the playoffs, in which Team Sweden won its second World Curling Championship bronze medal. He also made his first Olympic appearances with Team Edin, coming in fourth in the 2010 Winter Olympics and receiving a bronze medal in the 2014 Winter Olympics.\n\nWith his own team, however, Eriksson and his teammates were recognized as a very competitive team and won several international events, including the Oslo Cup (2009), Swiss Cup Basel (2012), and European Masters (2013), as well as the Winter Universiade (2013).<ref name=Erikssoncareer /> In the 2013-14 season, Team Eriksson reached second place at the Swiss Cup Basel, Mercure Perth Masters, and Sweden's Elite Series and competed in Canada on the World Curling Tour, coming in fifth place in three events and reaching their first Grand Slam Quarterfinal at the [[2014 The National (March)|National]]. Winning the Swedish Men's Curling Championships that year as well, the team was selected to represent Sweden in the [[2014 World Men's Curling Championship]], as Team Edin had represented Sweden in the European Curling Championships. Team Eriksson reached the final and won the silver medal in their World Curling Championship debut.\n\n=== Seniors II (2014-present): Team Edin ===\n\nIn May 2014, Edin and Team Eriksson came to an agreement to form a new Team Edin, with Edin skipping the team in the fourth position and Oskar Eriksson playing third along with Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m playing second and Christoffer Sundgren in the lead position.<ref name=nwt2014>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2014/05/13/edin-och-eriksson-bildar-supercurlinglag/ |title=Edin och Eriksson bilder supercurlinglag|publisher=Nya Wermlands-Tidningen |date= 13 May 2014|accessdate=2020-04-05}}.</ref> When Lindstr\u00f6m underwent surgery in 2016, Rasmus Wran\u00e5 took over as second. From the start, however, the new Team Edin team immediately saw their increased potential and aimed to become the number one team in the world.<ref name=nwt2014 /> Indeed,  Team Edin was ranked first at the end of the [[2016\u201317 curling season]] on both lists and finished in first place on the prize money list in the [[2017-18 curling season]]. The team also reached the finals of the European Curling Championships every year since forming a new team, winning gold in all years but one (2014-2017 and 2019) and winning silver once (2018). The team also secured medals in the finals of the World Curling Championships every year except 2016, winning three gold (2015, 2018 and 2019) and one silver (2017).\n\nAs part of Team Edin, Eriksson and his teammates have been consistently ranked in the top ten teams in the world since they joined forces, due to their performance in Canada and around the world. The team has reached the playoffs in 20 Grand Slam of Curling Events. In the 2016-17 season, Team Edin had their most successful year on tour, winning three Slams (the Masters, the Tour Challenge, and the Players\u2019 Championship) and reaching the finals (the Canadian Open) and semifinals (the National and Champions Cup) of all but one of the slams, securing the Pinty\u2019s Cup, the first non-Canadian men's team to do so. The Team has also won several other World Curling Tour events, including the European Masters (2014), Swiss Cup Basel (2016, 2018), Baden Masters (2015, 2017), Curling Masters Champery (2016, 2017), and Perth Masters (2018).<ref name=Erikssoncareer /> Team Edin has also won the [[Swedish Men's Curling Championships]] six times between 2014 and 2020, skipping only the 2017 championships to prepare for the World Championships.\n\n=== Career Achievements  ===\n\nCurrently, Eriksson is the only Swedish curler to have taken part in nine consecutive [[World Curling Championships]] in the men's division (2011-2019). Eriksson has also competed in eleven consecutive [[European Curling Championships]], winning a record seven gold medals, a record that he shares only with Niklas Edin. With Team Edin, Eriksson has won four World Curling Championship gold medals (in 2013, 2015, 2018 and 2019), placing him in an elite group of curlers to hold four World Championship titles.<ref>[[List of men%27s World Curling champions]]</ref> In 2019, Eriksson became the first curler in history to hold three key gold medals in a single calendar year: the [[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|World Curling Championship]], the [[2019 European Curling Championships|European Curling Championship]], and the [[2019 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship|World Mixed Doubles Championship]] (with Anna Hasselborg).<ref name=Erikssonhistoria /> As part of Team Edin, Eriksson, Niklas Edin, and Christoffer Sundgren also became the first men's curlers to simultaneously hold the World Curling Championship and European Curling Championship titles in two separate calendar years (2015 and 2019).<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_men%27s_World_Curling_champions and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Curling_Championships</ref> Eriksson and Edin had previously become the first men's curlers to simultaneously hold those same titles in three separate competition seasons (2012-2013, 2014\u20132015, and 2017-2018).<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_men%27s_World_Curling_champions and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Curling_Championships</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Eriksson was inducted into the [[Swedish Curling Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Grand Slam record==\n{{Curling GS key}}\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! [[2013-14 curling season|2013\u201314]]\n! [[2014-15 curling season|2014\u201315]]\n! [[2015\u201316 curling season|2015\u201316]]\n! [[2016\u201317 curling season|2016\u201317]]\n! [[2017\u201318 curling season|2017\u201318]]\n! [[2018\u201319 curling season|2018\u201319]]\n! [[2019\u201320 curling season|2019\u201320]]\n|-\n| [[Elite 10]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| F\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2016 Elite 10|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2017 Elite 10|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2018 Elite 10 (March)|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2018 Elite 10 (September)|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|-\n| [[Masters (curling)|Masters]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| QF\n|style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| '''[[2016 WFG Masters|C]]'''\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| F\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2018 Masters (curling)|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2019 Masters (curling)|Q]]\n|-\n| [[Tour Challenge]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| '''[[2016 GSOC Tour Challenge|C]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2017 GSOC Tour Challenge|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2018 Tour Challenge|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2019 Tour Challenge|QF]]\n|-\n| [[The National (curling)|The National]]\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| QF\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2015 The National|Q]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2016 The National|SF]]\n|style=\"bbackground:#afeeee;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2018 National|QF]]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| [[2019 National|F]]\n|-\n| [[Canadian Open (curling)|Canadian Open]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2015 Meridian Canadian Open|QF]]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| [[2017 Meridian Canadian Open|F]]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| [[2018 Meridian Canadian Open|F]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2019 Canadian Open (curling)|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|-\n| [[Players' Championships|Players']]\n|style=\"bbackground:#EFEFEF;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2016 Players' Championship|QF]]\n|style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| [[2017 Players' Championship|'''C''']]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| F\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2019 Players' Championship|QF]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|-\n| [[Champions Cup (curling)|Champions Cup]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2016 Humpty's Champions Cup|QF]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| SF\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2019 Champions Cup|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|}\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Season\n!Skip/Fourth\n!Third\n!Second\n!Lead\n!Alternate\n!Events\n|-\n| 2005\u201306|| [[Anders Eriksson (Karlstad curler)|Anders Eriksson]] (4th) || [[Sebastian Kraupp]] (skip) || [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' || ||\n|-\n| 2006\u201307|| '''Oskar Eriksson''' || Henric Jonsson || Markus Franz\u00e9n || Nils Karlsson || ||\n|-\n| 2007\u201308|| '''Oskar Eriksson''' || Henric Jonsson || Markus Franz\u00e9n || Nils Karlsson || || WJCC\n|-\n| 2008\u201309 || [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) || [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] || [[Henrik Leek]] || WJCC \n|-\n| 2009\u201310 || (1) [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) <br> (2) [[Niklas Edin]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) <br> [[Sebastian Kraupp]] || [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] <br> [[Fredrik Lindberg]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] <br> [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]] || <br> Oskar Eriksson ||  <br> ECC, [[Curling at the 2010 Winter Olympics|OG]]\n|-\n| 2010\u201311 || (1) [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) <br> (2) [[Niklas Edin]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) <br> [[Sebastian Kraupp]] || [[Henrik Leek]] <br> [[Fredrik Lindberg]] || [[Alexander Lindstr