{"title_page": "The Story of the Clash, Volume 1", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Story of the Clash, Volume 1\n| type       = Compilation album\n| artist     = [[The Clash]]\n| cover      = The story of the clash cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|2|29|df=y}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 100:10\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer   = The Clash, [[Mickey Foote]], [[Mikey Dread]], [[Sandy Pearlman]], [[Bill Price (record producer)|Bill Price]], [[Guy Stevens]], [[Lee \"Scratch\" Perry|Lee Perry]]\n| chronology = [[The Clash]] compilations and lives\n| prev_title = [[Super Black Market Clash#Black Market Clash|Black Market Clash]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[1977 Revisited]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n{{Album ratings | rev1 = [[Allmusic]] | rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r4102|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|accessdate=2011-06-28}}</ref> | rev2 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' | rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-story-of-the-clash-volume-1-19880714 Rolling Stone 14 July 1988]</ref>  | rev3 = [[Robert Christgau]] | rev3Score = C+<ref>Christgau, Robert. [http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=1400 The Clash]. Retrieved 2011-06-28.</ref> }}\n\n'''''The Story of the Clash, Vol. 1''''' is a double-disc compilation album by the English [[punk rock]] band [[The Clash]]. It was released with 28 tracks on 29 February 1988 through [[Epic Records]]. The compilation presents a relatively thorough overview of their career, but does not feature any material from their final studio album ''[[Cut the Crap]]''. An anticipated second volume was to have consisted of live recordings but remains unreleased. The original albums on vinyl were released with 4 different colored covers, Red, Blue, Yellow, and Green.\n\n==Track listing==\nThe 2\u00d7LP release of the album has the first six tracks of Disc 1 on Side A and the latter seven on Side B, and the first eight tracks of Disc 2 on Side C and the latter seven on Side D.\n\nAll songs written by [[Joe Strummer]] and [[Mick Jones (The Clash)|Mick Jones]] except where noted.\n\n===Disc 1===\n#\"[[The Magnificent Seven (song)|The Magnificent Seven]]\" \u2013 4:27 (the Clash) <small>(12\" version; original version from ''[[Sandinista!]]'', 1980)</small>\n#\"[[Rock the Casbah]]\" \u2013 3:42 (the Clash) <small>(US single mix; original version from ''[[Combat Rock]]'', 1982)</small>\n#\"[[This Is Radio Clash]]\" \u2013 4:10 (the Clash) <small>(A-side of non-album single, 1981)</small>\n#\"[[Should I Stay or Should I Go]]\" \u2013 3:06 (the Clash) <small>(from ''Combat Rock'', 1982)</small>\n#\"[[Straight to Hell (song)|Straight to Hell]]\" \u2013 5:30 (the Clash) <small>(from ''Combat Rock'', 1982)</small>\n#\"Armagideon Time\" \u2013 3:50 ([[Willi Williams]], [[Jackie Mittoo]]) <small>(B-side of \"London Calling\" single, 1979)</small>\n#\"[[Clampdown]]\" \u2013 3:50 <small>(from ''[[London Calling]]'', 1979)</small>\n#\"[[Train in Vain]]\" \u2013 3:10 <small>(from ''London Calling'', 1979)</small>\n#\"[[Guns of Brixton|The Guns of Brixton]]\" \u2013 3:12 (Simonon) <small>(from ''London Calling'', 1979)</small>\n#\"[[I Fought the Law#The Clash cover version|I Fought the Law]]\" \u2013 2:35 ([[Sonny Curtis]]) <small>(from ''The Cost of Living'' EP, 1979)</small>\n#\"[[Somebody Got Murdered]]\" \u2013 3:34 (the Clash) <small>(from ''[[Sandinista!]]'', 1980)</small>\n#\"[[Lost in the Supermarket]]\" \u2013 3:47 <small>(from ''London Calling'', 1979)</small>\n#\"[[Bankrobber]]\" \u2013 4:31 <small>(A-side of non-album single, 1980)</small>\n\n===Disc 2===\n#\"[[(White Man) In Hammersmith Palais]]\" \u2013 3:58 <small>(non-album single, 1978)</small>\n#\"[[London's Burning (The Clash song)|London's Burning]]\" \u2013 2:09 <small>(from ''[[The Clash (album)|The Clash]]'', 1977)</small>\n#\"[[Janie Jones (song)|Janie Jones]]\" \u2013 2:04 <small>(from ''The Clash'', 1977)</small>\n#\"[[Tommy Gun (song)|Tommy Gun]]\" \u2013 3:14 <small>(from ''[[Give 'Em Enough Rope]]'', 1978)</small>\n#\"[[Complete Control]]\" \u2013 3:12 <small>(non-album single, 1977)</small>\n#\"[[Capital Radio One]]\" (preceded by Circle Line interview part 2)<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Clash-Capital-Radio-EP/release/1495653 Discogs \u2013 ''Capital Radio E.P.'' 09th of April 1977 UK]</ref> \u2013 5:18 <small>(from ''Capital Radio'' EP, 1977)</small>\n#\"[[White Riot]]\" \u2013 1:59 <small>(single version, 18 March 1977)</small>\n#\"[[Career Opportunities (song)|Career Opportunities]]\" \u2013 1:51 <small>(from ''The Clash'', 1977)</small>\n#\"[[Clash City Rockers]]\" \u2013 3:57 <small>(non-album single, 1978)</small>\n#\"[[Safe European Home]]\" \u2013 3:49 <small>(from ''Give 'Em Enough Rope'', 1978)</small>\n#\"Stay Free\" \u2013 3:37 <small>(from ''Give 'Em Enough Rope'', 1978)</small>\n#\"[[London Calling]]\" \u2013 3:19 <small>(from ''London Calling'', 1979)</small>\n#\"[[Spanish Bombs]]\" \u2013 3:18 <small>(from ''London Calling'', 1979)</small>\n#\"[[English Civil War (song)|English Civil War]]\" (trad. arr. Strummer/Jones) \u2013 2:34 <small>(from ''Give 'Em Enough Rope'', 1978)</small>\n#\"[[Police and Thieves|Police & Thieves]]\" ([[Junior Murvin]], [[Lee \"Scratch\" Perry]]) \u2013 6:00 <small>(from ''The Clash'', 1977)</small>\n\n==Liner notes==\nThe extensive inner notes are told from the perspective of Joe Strummer's alter-ego, one Albert Transom. Transom, described by himself as \"...their valet from the early beginnings to the bitter end...\", tells many anecdotes, including one about the beginning of the rioting at the [[Notting Hill Carnival]] in 1976. Many of the stories are about shows, such as one where, after their \"3rd or 4th time out\", Transom and a fellow punk named Sebastian barricaded themselves in a small room and were attacked by a group of \"[[Teddy Boys]]\". The story went that Sebastian's tie was ripped, and the general consensus was that the tie was now \"much more punk\". Many other musicians are mentioned in the liners, including experiences with [[Bo Diddley]], [[Devo]], and [[Roxy Music]]. The notes end with \"If I had to sum it up, I'd say we played every gig on the face of the earth and that's what its all about...I've just heard they'll give me some room on Vol. 2 so maybe I will be able to tell the bits I've had to skip or leave out.\"<ref>{{cite AV media notes |last=Strummer |first=Joe |authorlink=Joe Strummer |title=The Story of the Clash, Volume 1 |others=The Clash |year=1988 |type=CD, 2\u00d7LP |publisher=CBS }}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n{| style=\"background: transparent none; border: 0 transparent none\"\n|-\n| style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-right: 1em\" |\n;The Clash\n* [[Joe Strummer]] \u2013 guitar, vocals\n* [[Mick Jones (The Clash)|Mick Jones]] \u2013 guitar, vocals\n* [[Paul Simonon]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Topper Headon]] \u2013 drums\n| style=\"vertical-align: top; padding-left: 1em\" |\n;Production\n* [[The Clash]] \u2013 producer\n* [[Guy Stevens]] \u2013 producer\n* Mickey Foote \u2013 producer\n* [[Sandy Pearlman]] \u2013 producer\n* [[Bob Clearmountain]] \u2013 engineering\n* Tricia Ronane \u2013 compiler\n* [[Pennie Smith]] \u2013 photography\n* Julian Balme (as Jules) \u2013 sleeve\n* Bob Whitney \u2013 remastering (1999 version)\n* [[Ray Staff]] \u2013 remastering (1999 version)\n|}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart \n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| {{Albumchart|Germany3|53|artist=The Clash|album=The Story Of The Clash }}\n|-\n| {{Albumchart|New Zealand|3|artist=The Clash|album=The Story Of The Clash}}\n|-\n| {{Albumchart|Sweden|50|artist=The Clash|album=The Story Of The Clash}}\n|-\n| {{Albumchart|UK2|7|artist=The Clash|date=1988-04-02}}\n|-\n| {{Albumchart|Billboard200|50|artist=The Clash|artistid=394493}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|artist=CLASH|title=THE STORY OF THE CLASH \u2013 VOL 1|award=Silver|type=album|date=1988-03-21}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|artist=CLASH|title=THE STORY OF THE CLASH \u2013 VOL 1|award=Gold|refname=xyzzy|type=album|date=1988-12-06}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=CLASH, THE|title=STORY OF THE CLASH|award=Gold|type=album|date=1999-04-20}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=CLASH, THE|title=STORY OF THE CLASH|award=Platinum|type=album|date=1999-04-20}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|noshipments=true}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MusicBrainz release|mbid=3cdf68e3-ea90-46e3-bfc2-630eca9ddc18|name=The Story of the Clash, Volume 1 (disc 1)}}\n* {{MusicBrainz release|mbid=64321cbb-a5c9-40e0-b35b-53f6b3701f04|name=The Story of the Clash, Volume 1 (disc 2)}}\n* [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r4102|pure_url=yes}} ''The Story of the Clash, Volume 1''] at [[Allmusic]]\n\n{{The Clash}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Story of the Clash}}\n[[Category:1988 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bill Price (record producer)]]\n[[Category:The Clash compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Epic Records compilation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Story of the Clash, Volume 1\n| type       = Compilation album\n| artist     = [[The Clash]]\n| cover      = The story of the clash cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|2|29|df=y}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 100:10\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer   = The Clash, [[Mickey Foote]], [[Mikey Dread]], [[Sandy Pearlman]], [[Bill Price (record producer)|Bill Price]], [[Guy Stevens]], [[Lee \"Scratch\" Perry|Lee Perry